q3.exp: more nodes would logically mean a greater difficulty in guessing passwords especially when you see someone put in their password. It would be harder to track movements. Only detractor would be small nodes, hard for you to hit correctly each time, or if one had large fingers.
q4.expl: The majority of people are right-handed, and we live in a society that writes left to right, top to bottom. I figured many people would begin at the top left. MIDN are often very logical thinkers and that caused me to guess patterns that didn't cross themselves.

q3.exp: big enough for variety not so big that you hit the wrong location often
q4.expl: What felt comfortable to me what other might think as seecure Ensuring that all boxes were selected

q3.exp: Balance between simplicity and security. A 5x5 grid is definitely more secure than a 3x3 against guesses, but it is still a small enough grid t maintain ease of use and simplicity for the user.
q4.expl: Alyways start on the outside edge where most people would start, and then keep the rest simple

q3.exp: 3x3 grids have siginificantly less possible atterns then 4x4 grid, and I'm sure I could create many more very difficult patterns with a larger grid
q4.expl: I picked patterns that were long but easy to input

q3.exp: Any grid larger could be cumbersome and irritating to get accurate on a small screen, however, a 6x6 offers a wider variety of combinations
q4.expl: I started from the upper right corner several times or I started making spirals from ther center.

Still small enough for easy to remember passwords but more secure than the 3x3 grid. If a grid is too large, then it may be too un-userfriendly.
